        "ulrome-περιγραφή-1": "Ulrome beach, on the Holderness coast of East Yorkshire, is not a classic fossil locality; the underlying Cretaceous chalk is buried beneath thick glacial sediments and rarely exposed. The fossils here are glacial erratics: during the last Ice Age, ice from northern Britain, Scotland and Scandinavia carried rocks and fossils into the Holderness coast, rapid cliff erosion now releases them, and longshore drift redistributes them along the beach.","ulrome-περιγραφή-2": "That makes Ulrome a geological grab-bag: one fossil may be Jurassic with ammonites or Gryphaea, another Cretaceous with belemnites or inoceramids, another Carboniferous with corals; the exact age and source of any single specimen is often uncertain. The palaeoenvironmental picture is therefore not a single scene but a mosaic of ancient seas: warm shallow shelves, chalky open marine settings, mollusc- and echinoid-rich seafloors, and patches of tropical coral reef.",
